# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thin-films
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] During atomic layer deposition, a film is grown on a substrate by exposing its surface to alternate gaseous species (typically referred to as precursors or reactants).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In contrast to chemical vapor deposition, the precursors are never present simultaneously in the reactor, but they are inserted as a series of sequential, non-overlapping pulses.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In each of these pulses the precursor molecules react with the surface in a self-limiting way, so that the reaction terminates once all the available sites on the surface are consumed.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Consequently, the maximum amount of material deposited on the surface after a single exposure to all of the precursors (a so-called ALD cycle) is determined by the nature of the precursor-surface interaction.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] By varying the number of cycles it is possible to grow materials uniformly and with high precision on arbitrarily complex and large substrates.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD is a deposition method with great potential for producing very thin, conformal films with control of the thickness and composition of the films possible at the atomic level.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] A major driving force for the recent interest is the prospective seen for ALD in scaling down microelectronic devices according to Moore's law.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD is an active field of research, with hundreds of different processes published in the scientific literature, though some of them exhibit behaviors that depart from that of an ideal ALD process.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Currently there are several comprehensive review papers that give a summary of the published ALD processes, including the work of Puurunen, Miikkulainen *et al.*, Knoops *et al.*, and Mackus & Schneider *et al.*.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] An interactive, community driven database of ALD processes is also available online which generates an up-to-date overview in the form of an annotated periodic table.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The sister technique of atomic layer deposition, molecular layer deposition (MLD), uses organic precursors to deposit polymers.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] By combining the ALD/MLD techniques, it is possible to make highly conformal and pure hybrid films for many applications.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Another technology related to ALD is sequential infiltration synthesis (SIS) which uses alternating precursor vapor exposures to infiltrate and modify polymers.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] SIS is also referred to as vapor phase infiltration (VPI) and sequential vapor infiltration (SVI).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In the 1960s, Stanislav Koltsov together with Valentin Aleskovsky and colleagues experimentally developed the principles of ALD at Leningrad Technological Institute (LTI) in the Soviet Union.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The purpose was to experimentally build upon the theoretical considerations of the "framework hypothesis" coined by Aleskovsky in his 1952 habilitation thesis.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The experiments started with metal chloride reactions and water with porous silica, soon extending to other substrate materials and planar thin films.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Aleskovskii and Koltsov together proposed the name "Molecular Layering" for the new technique in 1965.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The principles of Molecular Layering were summarized in the doctoral thesis ("professor's thesis") of Koltsov in 1971.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Research activities of molecular layering covered a broad scope, from fundamental chemistry research to applied research with porous catalysts, sorbents and fillers to microelectronics and beyond.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In 1974, when starting the development of thin-film electroluminescent displays (TFEL) at Instrumentarium Oy in Finland, Tuomo Suntola devised ALD as an advanced thin-film technology.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Suntola named it atomic layer epitaxy (ALE) based on the meaning of "epitaxy" in Greek language, "arrangement upon".
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The first experiments were made with elemental Zn and S to grow ZnS.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALE as a means for growth of thin films was internationally patented in more than 20 countries.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] A breakthrough occurred, when Suntola and co-workers switched from high vacuum reactors to inert gas reactors which enabled the use of compound reactants like metal chlorides, hydrogen sulfide and water vapor for performing the ALE process.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The technology was first disclosed in 1980 SID conference.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The TFEL display prototype presented consisted of a ZnS layer between two aluminum oxide dielectric layers, all made in an ALE process using ZnCl2 + H2S and AlCl3 + H2O as the reactants.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The first large-scale proof-of-concept of ALE-EL displays were the flight information boards installed in the Helsinki-Vantaa airport in 1983.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] TFEL flat panel display production started in the mid-1980s by Lohja Oy in the Olarinluoma factory.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Academic research on ALE started in Tampere University of Technology (where Suntola gave lectures on electron physics) in 1970s, and in 1980s at Helsinki University of Technology.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] TFEL display manufacturing remained until the 1990s the only industrial application of ALE.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In 1987, Suntola started the development of the ALE technology for new applications like photovoltaic devices and heterogeneous catalysts in Microchemistry Ltd., established for that purpose by the Finnish national oil company Neste Oy.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In the 1990s, ALE development in Microchemistry was directed to semiconductor applications and ALE reactors suitable for silicon wafer processing.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In 1999, Microchemistry Ltd. and the ALD technology were sold to the Dutch ASM International, a major supplier of semiconductor manufacturing equipment and Microchemistry Ltd. became ASM Microchemistry Oy as ASM's Finnish daughter company.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Microchemistry Ltd/ASM Microchemistry Ltd was the only manufacturer of commercial ALD-reactors in the 1990s.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In the early 2000s, the expertise on ALD reactors in Finland triggered two new manufacturers, Beneq Oy and Picosun Oy, the latter started by Sven Lindfors, Suntola's close coworker since 1975.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The number of reactor manufacturers increased rapidly and semiconductor applications became the industrial breakthrough of the ALD technology, as ALD became an enabling technology for the continuation of Moore's law.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In 2004, Tuomo Suntola received the European SEMI award for the development of the ALD technology for semiconductor applications and in 2018 the Millennium Technology Prize.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The developers of ML and ALE met at the 1st international conference on atomic layer epitaxy, "ALE-1" in Espoo, Finland, 1990.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] An attempt to expose the extent of molecular layering works was made in a scientific ALD review article in 2005 and later in the VPHA-related publications.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The name "atomic layer deposition" was apparently proposed for the first time in writing as an alternative to ALE in analogy with CVD by Markku Leskelä (professor at the University of Helsinki) at the ALE-1 conference, Espoo, Finland.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] It took about a decade before the name gained general acceptance with the onset of the international conference series on ALD by American Vacuum Society.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In 2000, Gurtej Singh Sandhu and Trung T.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Doan of Micron Technology initiated the development of atomic layer deposition high-κ films for DRAM memory devices.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] This helped drive cost-effective implementation of semiconductor memory, starting with 90-nm node DRAM.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Intel Corporation has reported using ALD to deposit high-κ gate dielectric for its 45 nm CMOS technology.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD has been developed in two independent discoveries under names atomic layer epitaxy (ALE, Finland) and molecular layering (ML, Soviet Union).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] To clarify the early history, the Virtual Project on the History of ALD (VPHA) has been set up in summer 2013.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] It resulted in several publications reviewing the historical development of ALD under the names ALE and ML.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In a prototypical ALD process, a substrate is exposed to two reactants A and B in a sequential, non-overlapping way.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In contrast to other techniques such as chemical vapor deposition (CVD), where thin-film growth proceeds on a steady-state fashion, in ALD each reactant reacts with the surface in a self-limited way: the reactant molecules can react only with a finite number of reactive sites on the surface.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Once all those sites have been consumed in the reactor, the growth stops.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The remaining reactant molecules are flushed away and only then reactant B is inserted into the reactor.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] By alternating exposures of A and B, a thin film is deposited.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] This process is shown in the side figure.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Consequently, when describing an ALD process one refers to both dose times (the time a surface is being exposed to a precursor) and purge times (the time left in between doses for the precursor to evacuate the chamber) for each precursor.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The dose-purge-dose-purge sequence of a binary ALD process constitutes an ALD cycle.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Also, rather than using the concept of growth rate, ALD processes are described in terms of their growth per cycle.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In ALD, enough time must be allowed in each reaction step so that a full adsorption density can be achieved.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] When this happens the process has reached saturation.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] This time will depend on two key factors: the precursor pressure, and the sticking probability.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Where R is the rate of adsorption, S is the sticking probability, and F is the incident molar flux.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] However, a key characteristic of ALD is the S will change with time, as more molecules have reacted with the surface this sticking probability will become smaller until reaching a value of zero once saturation is reached.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The specific details on the reaction mechanisms are strongly dependent on the particular ALD process.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] With hundreds of process available to deposit oxide, metals, nitrides, sulfides, chalcogenides, and fluoride materials, the unraveling of the mechanistic aspects of ALD processes is an active field of research.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Some representative examples are shown below.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Thermal ALD requires temperatures ranging from room temperature (~20°C) to 350°C for ligand exchange or combustion type surface reactions.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] It occurs through surface reactions, which enables accurate thickness control no matter the substrate geometry (subject to aspect ratio) and reactor design.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The synthesis of Al2O3 from trimethylaluminum (TMA) and water is one of the best known thermal ALD examples.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] During the TMA exposure, TMA dissociatively chemisorbs on the substrate surface and any remaining TMA is pumped out of the chamber.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The dissociative chemisorption of TMA leaves a surface covered with AlCH3.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The surface is then exposed to H2O vapor, which reacts with the surface –CH3 forming CH4 as a reaction byproduct and resulting in a hydroxylated Al2O3 surface.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In plasma-assisted ALD (PA-ALD), the high reactivity of the plasma species allows to reduce the deposition temperature without compromising the film quality; also, a wider range of precursors can be used and thus a wider range of materials can be deposited as compared to thermal ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] PA-ALD can also deliver higher thickness control as well as uniformity in deposition.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In temporal ALD the separate precursor and co-reactant doses are separated from each other in *time* by a purge step.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In contrast, in spatial ALD (s-ALD), these gases are delivered at different locations, so they are separated in *space*.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In atmospheric pressure s-ALD the precursor and co-reactant are delivered continuously and they are separated from each other by a gas curtain to prevent gas phase reactions.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Such gas curtain typically consists of nitrogen injection and exhaust positions, see Figure 1.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] As a substrates moves through the different gas zones, self-limiting reactions take place at the substrate surface and the ALD process takes place.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] As this process can easily be accelerated, the deposition rate for spatial ALD can be much higher than for conventional ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] For example, for ALD of Al2O3 the deposition rate increases from 100-300 nm per hour to 60 nm per minute.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The inline nature of spatial ALD makes it suitable for high volume production lines and roll-to-roll production.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In general, s-ALD has been employed to apply moisture permeation barriers, passivation layers in silicon solar cells and functional layers in batteries.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Additionally, organic molecules can be grown in combination with inorganic atoms to enable molecular layer deposition (MLD).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Plasma- or ozon enhanced spatial ALD has been demonstrated which generally lowers the deposition temperatures required.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In this ALD variety, UV light is used to accelerate surface reactions on the substrate.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Hence reaction temperature can be reduced, as in plasma-assisted ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] As compared to plasma-assisted ALD, the activation is weaker, but is often easier to control by adjusting the wavelength, intensity and timing of illumination.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Copper metal ALD has attracted much attention due to the demand for copper as an interconnect material and the relative ease by which copper can be deposited thermally.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Copper has a positive standard electrochemical potential and is the most easily reduced metal of the first-row transition metals.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Thus, numerous ALD processes have been developed, including several using hydrogen gas as the coreactant.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Ideally, copper metal ALD should be performed at ≤100 °C to achieve continuous films with low surface roughness, since higher temperatures can result in agglomeration of deposited copper.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Some metals can be grown by ALD via fluorosilane elimination reactions using a metal halide and a silicon precursor (e.g.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] These reactions are very exothermic due to the formation of stable Si–F bonds.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Metals deposited by fluorosilane elimination include tungsten and molybdenum.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The growth rate can vary from 4 to 7 Å/cycle depending on the deposition temperature (177 to 325 °C) and Si2H6 reactant exposure (~104 to 106 L), factors that may influence Si2H6 insertion into Si–H bonds and result in a silicon CVD contribution to the tungsten ALD growth.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The thermal ALD of many other metals is challenging (or presently impossible) due to their very negative electrochemical potentials.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Recently, the application of novel strong reducing agents has led to the first reports of low-temperature thermal ALD processes for several electropositive metals.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Chromium metal was deposited using a chromium alkoxide precursor and BH3(NHMe2).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Titanium and tin metals were grown from their respective metal chlorides (MCl4, M = Ti, Sn) and a bis(trimethylsilyl) six-membered ring compound.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Aluminum metal was deposited using an aluminum dihydride precursor and AlCl3.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The use of catalysts is of paramount importance in delivering reliable methods of SiO2 ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Without catalysts, surface reactions leading to the formation of SiO2 are generally very slow and only occur at exceptionally high temperatures.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Typical catalysts for SiO2 ALD include Lewis bases such as NH3 or pyridine and SiO2; ALD can also be initiated when these Lewis bases are coupled with other silicon precursors such as tetraethoxysilane (TEOS).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Hydrogen bonding is believed to occur between the Lewis base and the SiOH* surface species or between the H2O based reactant and the Lewis base.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Oxygen becomes a stronger nucleophile when the Lewis base hydrogen bonds with the SiOH* surface species because the SiO-H bond is effectively weakened.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] As such, the electropositive Si atom in the SiCl4 reactant is more susceptible to nucleophilic attack.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Similarly, hydrogen bonding between a Lewis base and an H2O reactant make the electronegative O in H2O a strong nucleophile that is able to attack the Si in an existing SiCl* surface species.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The use of a Lewis base catalyst is more or less a requirement for SiO2 ALD, as without a Lewis base catalyst, reaction temperatures must exceed 325 °C and pressures must exceed 103 torr.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Generally, the most favorable temperature to perform SiO2 ALD is at 32 °C and a common deposition rate is 1.35 angstroms per binary reaction sequence.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Two surface reactions for SiO2 ALD, an overall reaction, and a schematic illustrating Lewis base catalysis in SiO2 ALD are provided below.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD is a useful process for the fabrication of microelectronics due to its ability to produce accurate thicknesses and uniform surfaces in addition to high quality film production using various different materials.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In microelectronics, ALD is studied as a potential technique to deposit high-κ (high permittivity) gate oxides, high-κ memory capacitor dielectrics, ferroelectrics, and metals and nitrides for electrodes and interconnects.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In high-κ gate oxides, where the control of ultra thin films is essential, ALD is only likely to come into wider use at the 45 nm technology.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In metallizations, conformal films are required; currently it is expected that ALD will be used in mainstream production at the 65 nm node.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In dynamic random access memories (DRAMs), the conformality requirements are even higher and ALD is the only method that can be used when feature sizes become smaller than 100 nm.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Several products that use ALD include magnetic recording heads, MOSFET gate stacks, DRAM capacitors, nonvolatile ferroelectric memories, and many others.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Deposition of the high-κ oxides Al2O3, ZrO2, and HfO2 has been one of the most widely examined areas of ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The motivation for high-κ oxides comes from the problem of high tunneling current through the commonly used SiO2 gate dielectric in MOSFETs when it is downscaled to a thickness of 1.0 nm and below.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] With the high-κ oxide, a thicker gate dielectric can be made for the required capacitance density, thus the tunneling current can be reduced through the structure.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Transition-metal nitrides, such as TiN and TaN, find potential use both as metal barriers and as gate metals.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The metal barriers have strict demands: they should be pure; dense; conductive; conformal; thin; have good adhesion towards metals and insulators.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The requirements concerning process technique can be fulfilled by ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The most studied ALD nitride is TiN which is deposited from TiCl4 and NH3.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] 4. high- and low-work function metals for dual-gate MOSFETs.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Magnetic recording heads utilize electric fields to polarize particles and leave a magnetized pattern on a hard disk.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Al2O3 ALD is used to create uniform, thin layers of insulation.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] By using ALD, it is possible to control the insulation thickness to a high level of accuracy.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] This allows for more accurate patterns of magnetized particles and thus higher quality recordings.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] DRAM capacitors are yet another application of ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] An individual DRAM cell can store a single bit of data and consists of a single MOS transistor and a capacitor.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Major efforts are being put into reducing the size of the capacitor which will effectively allow for greater memory density.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In order to change the capacitor size without affecting the capacitance, different cell orientations are being used.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Some of these include stacked or trench capacitors.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] With the emergence of trench capacitors, the problem of fabricating these capacitors comes into play, especially as the size of semiconductors decreases.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD allows trench features to be scaled to beyond 100 nm.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The ability to deposit single layers of material allows for a great deal of control over the material.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Except for some issues of incomplete film growth (largely due to insufficient amount or low temperature substrates), ALD provides an effective means of depositing thin films like dielectrics or barriers.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The use of ALD technique in solar cells is becoming more prominent with time.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In the past, it has been used to deposit surface passivation layers in crystalline-silicon (c-Si) solar cells, buffer layers in copper indium gallium selenide (CIGS) solar cells and barrier layers in dye-sensitized solar cells (DSSCs).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] For e.g., the use of ALD grown Al2O3 for solar cell applications was demonstrated by Schmidt *et al*.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] It was used as a surface passivation layer for the development of PERC (passivated emitter and rear cell) solar cells.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The use of ALD technique to deposit charge transport layers (CTLs) is also being explored widely for perovskite solar cells.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The ability of ALD to deposit high quality and conformal films with precise control on thickness can provide great advantage in finely tailoring the interfaces between CTL and perovskite layer.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Moreover, it can be useful in obtaining uniform and pin-hole free films over large areas.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] These aspects make ALD a promising technique in further improving and stabilizing the performance of perovskite solar cells.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] As photonic integrated circuits (PICs) emerge, often in a manner similar to electronic integrated circuits, a wide variety of on-chip optical device structures are needed.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Understanding and being able to specify the surface properties on biomedical devices is critical in the biomedical industry, especially regarding devices that are implanted in the body.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] A material interacts with the environment at its surface, so the surface properties largely direct the interactions of the material with its environment.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Surface chemistry and surface topography affect protein adsorption, cellular interactions, and the immune response.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Some current uses in biomedical applications include creating flexible sensors, modifying nanoporous membranes, polymer ALD, and creating thin biocompatible coatings.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD has been used to deposit TiO2 films to create optical waveguide sensors as diagnostic tools.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Also, ALD is beneficial in creating flexible sensing devices that can be used, for example, in the clothing of athletes to detect movement or heart rate.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD is one possible manufacturing process for flexible organic field-effect transistors (OFETs) because it is a low-temperature deposition method.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Nanoporous materials are emerging throughout the biomedical industry in drug delivery, implants, and tissue engineering.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The benefit of using ALD to modify the surfaces of nanoporous materials is that, unlike many other methods, the saturation and self-limiting nature of the reactions means that even deeply embedded surfaces and interfaces are coated with a uniform film.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Nanoporous surfaces can have their pore size reduced further in the ALD process because the conformal coating will completely coat the insides of the pores.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] This reduction in pore size may be advantageous in certain applications.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD can be used as a permeation barrier for plastics.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] For example, it is well established as a method for encapsulation of OLEDs on plastic.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD can also be used to inoculate 3-D printed plastic parts for use in vacuum environments by mitigating outgassing, which allows for custom low-cost tools for both semiconductor processing and space applications.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD can be used to form a barrier on plastics in roll to roll processes.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The quality of an ALD process can be monitored using several different imaging techniques to make sure that the ALD process is occurring smoothly and producing a conformal layer over a surface.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] One option is the use of cross-sectional scanning electron microscopy (SEM) or transmission electron microscopy (TEM).
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] High magnification of images is pertinent for assessing the quality of an ALD layer.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] X-ray reflectivity (XRR) is a technique that measures thin-film properties including thickness, density, and surface roughness.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Another optical quality evaluation tool is spectroscopic ellipsometry.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Its application between the depositions of each layer by ALD provides information on the growth rate and material characteristics of the film.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Applying this analysis tool during the ALD process, sometimes referred to as *in situ* spectroscopic ellipsometry, allows for greater control over the growth rate of the films during the ALD process.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] This type of quality control occurs during the ALD process rather than assessing the films afterwards as in TEM imaging, or XRR.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Additionally, Rutherford backscattering spectroscopy (RBS), X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS), Auger electron spectroscopy (AES), and four-terminal sensing can be used to provide quality control information with regards to thin films deposited by ALD.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD provides a very controlled method to produce a film to an atomically specified thickness.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Also, the growth of different multilayer structures is straightforward.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Because of the sensitivity and precision of the equipment, it is very beneficial to those in the field of microelectronics and nanotechnology in producing small, but efficient semiconductors.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD typically involves the use of relatively low temperatures and a catalyst, which is thermochemically favored.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The lower temperature is beneficial when working with soft substrates, such as organic and biological samples.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Some precursors that are thermally unstable still may be used so long as their decomposition rate is relatively slow.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] High purity of the substrates is very important, and as such, high costs will ensue.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Although this cost may not be much relative to the cost of the equipment needed, one may need to run several trials before finding conditions that favor their desired product.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Once the layer has been made and the process is complete, there may be a requirement of needing to remove excess precursors from the final product.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In some final products there are less than 1% of impurities present.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Atomic layer deposition instruments can range anywhere from $200,000 to $800,000 based on the quality and efficiency of the instrument.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] There is no set cost for running a cycle of these instruments; the cost varies depending on the quality and purity of the substrates used, as well as the temperature and time of machine operation.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Some substrates are less available than others and require special conditions, as some are very sensitive to oxygen and may then increase the rate of decomposition.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Multicomponent oxides and certain metals traditionally needed in the microelectronics industry are generally not cost efficient.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] The process of ALD is very slow and this is known to be its major limitation.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] For example, Al2O3 is deposited at a rate of 0.11 nm per cycle, which can correspond to an average deposition rate of 100–300 nm per hour, depending on cycle duration and pumping speed.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] This problem can be overrun by using Spatial ALD, where the substrate is moved in space below a special ALD showerhead, and both the precursor gasses are separated by gas curtains/bearings.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] In this way, deposition rates of 60 nm per minute could be reached.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] ALD is typically used to produce substrates for microelectronics and nanotechnology, and therefore, thick atomic layers are not needed.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Many substrates cannot be used because of their fragility or impurity.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Impurities are typically found on the 0.1–1 at.% because of some of the carrier gases are known to leave residue and are also sensitive to oxygen.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Precursors must be volatile, but not subject to decomposition, as most precursors are very sensitive to oxygen/air, thus causing a limitation on the substrates that may be used.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] Some biological substrates are very sensitive to heat and may have fast decomposition rates that are not favored and yield larger impurity levels.
[src:thin-films/atomic-layer-deposition] There are a multitude of thin-film substrate materials available, but the important substrates needed for use in microelectronics can be hard to obtain and may be very expensive.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] In typical CVD, the wafer (substrate) is exposed to one or more volatile precursors, which react and/or decompose on the substrate surface, in order to produce the desired deposit.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Frequently, volatile by-products are also produced, which are removed by gas flow through the reaction chamber.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Microfabrication processes widely use CVD to deposit materials in various forms, including: monocrystalline, polycrystalline, amorphous, and epitaxial.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] These materials include: silicon (dioxide, carbide, nitride, oxynitride), carbon (fiber, nanofibers, nanotubes, diamond and graphene), fluorocarbons, filaments, tungsten, titanium nitride and various high-κ dielectrics.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The term *chemical vapour deposition* was coined in 1960 by John M.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Blocher, Jr. who intended to differentiate *chemical* from *physical vapour deposition* (PVD).
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD is practiced in a variety of formats.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] These processes generally differ in the means by which chemical reactions are initiated.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Most modern CVD is either LPCVD or UHVCVD.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD is commonly used to deposit conformal films and augment substrate surfaces in ways that more traditional surface modification techniques are not capable of.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD is extremely useful in the process of atomic layer deposition at depositing extremely thin layers of material.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] A variety of applications for such films exist.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Gallium arsenide is used in some integrated circuits (ICs) and photovoltaic devices.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Amorphous polysilicon is used in photovoltaic devices.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Certain carbides and nitrides confer wear-resistance.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Polymerization by CVD, perhaps the most versatile of all applications, allows for super-thin coatings which possess some very desirable qualities, such as lubricity, hydrophobicity and weather-resistance to name a few.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The CVD of metal-organic frameworks, a class of crystalline nanoporous materials, has recently been demonstrated.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Recently scaled up as an integrated cleanroom process depositing large-area substrates, the applications for these films are anticipated in gas sensing and low-κ dielectrics.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD techniques are advantageous for membrane coatings as well, such as those in desalination or water treatment, as these coatings can be sufficiently uniform (conformal) and thin that they do not clog membrane pores.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] This reaction is usually performed in LPCVD systems, with either pure silane feedstock, or a solution of silane with 70–80% nitrogen.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Temperatures between 600 and 650 °C, and pressures between 25 and 150 Pa yield a growth rate between 10 and 20 nm per minute.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] An alternative process uses a hydrogen-based solution.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The hydrogen reduces the growth rate, but the temperature is raised to 850 or even 1050 °C to compensate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Polysilicon may be grown directly with doping, if gases such as phosphine, arsine or diborane are added to the CVD chamber.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Diborane increases the growth rate, but arsine and phosphine decrease it.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Silicon dioxide (usually called simply "oxide" in the semiconductor industry) may be deposited by several different processes.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Common source gases include silane and oxygen, dichlorosilane (SiCl2H2) and nitrous oxide (N2O), or tetraethylorthosilicate (TEOS; Si(OC2H5)4).
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The choice of source gas depends on the thermal stability of the substrate; for instance, aluminium is sensitive to high temperature.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Silane deposits between 300 and 500 °C, dichlorosilane at around 900 °C, and TEOS between 650 and 750 °C, resulting in a layer of *low- temperature oxide* (LTO).
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] However, silane produces a lower-quality oxide than the other methods (lower dielectric strength, for instance), and it deposits nonconformally.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Any of these reactions may be used in LPCVD, but the silane reaction is also done in APCVD.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD oxide invariably has lower quality than thermal oxide, but thermal oxidation can only be used in the earliest stages of IC manufacturing.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Oxide may also be grown with impurities (alloying or "doping").
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] During further process steps that occur at high temperature, the impurities may diffuse from the oxide into adjacent layers (most notably silicon) and dope them.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Oxides containing 5–15% impurities by mass are often used for this purpose.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] In addition, silicon dioxide alloyed with phosphorus pentoxide ("P-glass") can be used to smooth out uneven surfaces.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] P-glass softens and reflows at temperatures above 1000 °C.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] This process requires a phosphorus concentration of at least 6%, but concentrations above 8% can corrode aluminium.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Glasses containing both boron and phosphorus (borophosphosilicate glass, BPSG) undergo viscous flow at lower temperatures; around 850 °C is achievable with glasses containing around 5 weight % of both constituents, but stability in air can be difficult to achieve.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Phosphorus oxide in high concentrations interacts with ambient moisture to produce phosphoric acid.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Crystals of BPO4 can also precipitate from the flowing glass on cooling; these crystals are not readily etched in the standard reactive plasmas used to pattern oxides, and will result in circuit defects in integrated circuit manufacturing.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Besides these intentional impurities, CVD oxide may contain byproducts of the deposition.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] TEOS produces a relatively pure oxide, whereas silane introduces hydrogen impurities, and dichlorosilane introduces chlorine.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Lower temperature deposition of silicon dioxide and doped glasses from TEOS using ozone rather than oxygen has also been explored (350 to 500 °C).
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Ozone glasses have excellent conformality but tend to be hygroscopic – that is, they absorb water from the air due to the incorporation of silanol (Si-OH) in the glass.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Infrared spectroscopy and mechanical strain as a function of temperature are valuable diagnostic tools for diagnosing such problems.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Silicon nitride is often used as an insulator and chemical barrier in manufacturing ICs.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Silicon nitride deposited by LPCVD contains up to 8% hydrogen.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] It also experiences strong tensile stress, which may crack films thicker than 200 nm.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] However, it has higher resistivity and dielectric strength than most insulators commonly available in microfabrication (1016 Ω·cm and 10 MV/cm, respectively).
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] These films have much less tensile stress, but worse electrical properties (resistivity 106 to 1015 Ω·cm, and dielectric strength 1 to 5 MV/cm).
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Titanium nitride (TiN) is a commonly used as a wear resistant coating to increase the lifetime of cutting tools due to its hardness and chemical resistance.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Other gas mixtures used to deposit titanium nitride with CVD includes TiCl4 + NH3 + H2.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Other metals, notably aluminium and copper, can be deposited by CVD.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] As of 2010, commercially cost-effective CVD for copper did not exist, although volatile sources exist, such as Cu(hfac)2.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Copper is typically deposited by electroplating.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Aluminium can be deposited from triisobutylaluminium (TIBAL) and related organoaluminium compounds.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD for molybdenum, tantalum, titanium, nickel is widely used.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] These metals can form useful silicides when deposited onto silicon.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Mo, Ta, and Ti are deposited by LPCVD, from their pentachlorides.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] However, nickel, molybdenum, and tungsten can be deposited at low temperatures from their carbonyl precursors.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] the decomposition of metal carbonyls is often violently precipitated by moisture or air, where oxygen reacts with the metal precursor to form metal or metal oxide along with carbon dioxide.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Late transition metals are particularly difficult to deposit through CVD; see chemical vapor deposition of ruthenium.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Many variations of CVD can be utilized to synthesize graphene.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Although many advancements have been made, the processes listed below are not commercially viable yet.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The most popular carbon source that is used to produce graphene is methane gas.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] One of the less popular choices is petroleum asphalt, notable for being inexpensive but more difficult to work with.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Although methane is the most popular carbon source, hydrogen is required during the preparation process to promote carbon deposition on the substrate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] If the flow ratio of methane and hydrogen are not appropriate, it will cause undesirable results.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] During the growth of graphene, the role of methane is to provide a carbon source, the role of hydrogen is to provide H atoms to corrode amorphous C, and improve the quality of graphene.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] But excessive H atoms can also corrode graphene.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] As a result, the integrity of the crystal lattice is destroyed, and the quality of graphene is deteriorated.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Therefore, by optimizing the flow rate of methane and hydrogen gases in the growth process, the quality of graphene can be improved.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The use of catalyst is viable in changing the physical process of graphene production.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Notable examples include iron nanoparticles, nickel foam, and gallium vapor.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] These catalysts can either be used in situ during graphene buildup, or situated at some distance away at the deposition area.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Some catalysts require another step to remove them from the sample material.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The direct growth of high-quality, large single-crystalline domains of graphene on a dielectric substrate is of vital importance for applications in electronics and optoelectronics.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Combining the advantages of both catalytic CVD and the ultra-flat dielectric substrate, gaseous catalyst-assisted CVD paves the way for synthesizing high-quality graphene for device applications while avoiding the transfer process.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Physical conditions such as surrounding pressure, temperature, carrier gas, and chamber material play a big role in production of graphene.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Most systems use LPCVD with pressures ranging from 1 to 1500 Pa.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Low pressures are used more commonly as they help prevent unwanted reactions and produce more uniform thickness of deposition on the substrate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] On the other hand, temperatures used range from 800 to 1050 °C.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] High temperatures translate to an increase of the rate of reaction.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Caution has to be exercised as high temperatures do pose higher danger levels in addition to greater energy costs.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Hydrogen gas and inert gases such as argon are flowed into the system.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] These gases act as a carrier, enhancing surface reaction and improving reaction rate, thereby increasing deposition of graphene onto the substrate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Standard quartz tubing and chambers are used in CVD of graphene.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Quartz is chosen because it has a very high melting point and is chemically inert.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] In other words, quartz does not interfere with any physical or chemical reactions regardless of the conditions.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Raman spectroscopy, X-ray spectroscopy, transmission electron microscopy (TEM), and scanning electron microscopy (SEM) are used to examine and characterize the graphene samples.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Raman spectroscopy is used to characterize and identify the graphene particles; X-ray spectroscopy is used to characterize chemical states; TEM is used to provide fine details regarding the internal composition of graphene; SEM is used to examine the surface and topography.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Sometimes, atomic force microscopy (AFM) is used to measure local properties such as friction and magnetism.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] X-ray diffraction methods are useful techniques to analyze thin films.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] X-ray diffraction methods such as Grazing incidence X-ray diffraction can be used to qualify the phases present in deposited films.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Additionally, X-ray reflectivity (XRR) can be used to measure the thickness and roughness of deposited films.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Pole figure measurements are useful and can be used to investigate textures and preferential orientations in deposited films.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Cold wall CVD technique can be used to study the underlying surface science involved in graphene nucleation and growth as it allows unprecedented control of process parameters like gas flow rates, temperature and pressure as demonstrated in a recent study.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The study was carried out in a home-built vertical cold wall system utilizing resistive heating by passing direct current through the substrate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] It provided conclusive insight into a typical surface-mediated nucleation and growth mechanism involved in two-dimensional materials grown using catalytic CVD under conditions sought out in the semiconductor industry.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] In spite of graphene's exciting electronic and thermal properties, it is unsuitable as a transistor for future digital devices, due to the absence of a bandgap between the conduction and valence bands.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] This makes it impossible to switch between on and off states with respect to electron flow.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Scaling things down, graphene nanoribbons of less than 10 nm in width do exhibit electronic bandgaps and are therefore potential candidates for digital devices.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Precise control over their dimensions, and hence electronic properties, however, represents a challenging goal, and the ribbons typically possess rough edges that are detrimental to their performance.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD can be used to produce a synthetic diamond by creating the circumstances necessary for carbon atoms in a gas to settle on a substrate in crystalline form.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD of diamonds has received much attention in the materials sciences because it allows many new applications that had previously been considered too expensive.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD diamond growth typically occurs under low pressure (1–27 kPa; 0.145–3.926 psi; 7.5–203 Torr) and involves feeding varying amounts of gases into a chamber, energizing them and providing conditions for diamond growth on the substrate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The gases always include a carbon source, and typically include hydrogen as well, though the amounts used vary greatly depending on the type of diamond being grown.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Energy sources include hot filament, microwave power, and arc discharges, among others.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The energy source is intended to generate a plasma in which the gases are broken down and more complex chemistries occur.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The actual chemical process for diamond growth is still under study and is complicated by the very wide variety of diamond growth processes used.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Using CVD, films of diamond can be grown over large areas of substrate with control over the properties of the diamond produced.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] In the past, when high pressure high temperature (HPHT) techniques were used to produce a diamond, the result was typically very small free-standing diamonds of varying sizes.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] With CVD diamond, growth areas of greater than fifteen centimeters (six inches) in diameter have been achieved, and much larger areas are likely to be successfully coated with diamond in the future.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Improving this process is key to enabling several important applications.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] The growth of diamond directly on a substrate allows the addition of many of diamond's important qualities to other materials.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Since diamond has the highest thermal conductivity of any bulk material, layering diamond onto high heat-producing electronics (such as optics and transistors) allows the diamond to be used as a heat sink.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Diamond films are being grown on valve rings, cutting tools, and other objects that benefit from diamond's hardness and exceedingly low wear rate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] In each case the diamond growth must be carefully done to achieve the necessary adhesion onto the substrate.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] CVD growth allows one to control the properties of the diamond produced.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] In the area of diamond growth, the word "diamond" is used as a description of any material primarily made up of sp3-bonded carbon, and there are many different types of diamond included in this.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] By regulating the processing parameters—especially the gases introduced, but also including the pressure the system is operated under, the temperature of the diamond, and the method of generating plasma—many different materials that can be considered diamond can be made.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Single-crystal diamond can be made containing various dopants.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Polycrystalline diamond consisting of grain sizes from several nanometers to several micrometers can be grown.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Some polycrystalline diamond grains are surrounded by thin, non-diamond carbon, while others are not.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] These different factors affect the diamond's hardness, smoothness, conductivity, optical properties and more.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Commercially, mercury cadmium telluride is of continuing interest for detection of infrared radiation.
[src:thin-films/chemical-vapor-deposition] Consisting of an alloy of CdTe and HgTe, this material can be prepared from the dimethyl derivatives of the respective elements.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The term *epitaxy* comes from the Greek roots *epi* (ἐπί), meaning "above", and *taxis* (τάξις), meaning "an ordered manner".
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] One of the main commercial applications of epitaxial growth is in the semiconductor industry, where semiconductor films are grown epitaxially on semiconductor substrate wafers.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] For the case of epitaxial growth of a planar film atop a substrate wafer, the epitaxial film's lattice will have a specific orientation relative to the substrate wafer's crystalline lattice, such as the [001] Miller index of the film aligning with the [001] index of the Substrate.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In the simplest case, the epitaxial layer can be a continuation of the same semiconductor compound as the substrate; this is referred to as homoepitaxy.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Otherwise, the epitaxial layer will be composed of a different compound; this is referred to as heteroepitaxy.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Heteroepitaxy occurs when a film of different composition and/or crystalline films grown on a substrate.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Where $a_{f}$ and $a_{s}$ are the lattice constants of the film and the substrate.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The film and substrate could have similar lattice spacings but also different thermal expansion coefficients.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] If a film is grown at a high temperature, it can experience large strains upon cooling to room temperature.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In reality, $\varepsilon <9\%$ is necessary for obtaining epitaxy.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] If $\varepsilon$ is larger than that, the film experiences a volumetric strain that builds with each layer until a critical thickness.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] With increased thickness, the elastic strain in the film is relieved by the formation of dislocations, which can become scattering centers that damage the quality of the structure.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Heteroepitaxy is commonly used to create so-called bandgap systems thanks to the additional energy caused by de deformation.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Silicon-germanium epitaxial layers are heavily used in CMOS microelectronics and silicon photonics.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Epitaxy is used in silicon-based manufacturing processes for bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) and modern complementary metal–oxide–semiconductors (CMOS), but it is particularly important for compound semiconductors such as gallium arsenide.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Heteroepitaxial growth is classified into three primary growth modes-- **Volmer–Weber** (VW), **Frank–van der Merwe** (FM) and **Stranski–Krastanov** (SK).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In the VW growth regime, the epitaxial film grows out of 3D nuclei on the growth surface.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In this mode, the adsorbate-adsorbate interactions are stronger than adsorbate-surface interactions, leading to island formation by local nucleation and the epitaxial layer is formed when the islands join.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In the FM growth mode, adsorbate-surface and adsorbate-adsorbate interactions are balanced, which promotes 2D layer-by-layer or step-flow epitaxial growth.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The SK mode is a combination of VW and FM modes.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In this mechanism, the growth initiates in the FM mode, forming 2D layers, but after reaching a critical thickness, enters a VW-like 3D island growth regime.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Practical epitaxial growth, however, takes place in a high supersaturation regime, away from thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In that case, the epitaxial growth is governed by adatom kinetics rather than thermodynamics, and 2D step-flow growth becomes dominant.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Homoepitaxial growth of semiconductor thin films are generally done by chemical or physical vapor deposition methods that deliver the precursors to the substrate in gaseous state.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] where (g) and (s) represent gas and solid phases, respectively.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] This reaction is reversible, and the growth rate depends strongly upon the proportion of the two source gases.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Growth rates above 2 micrometres per minute produce polycrystalline silicon, and negative growth rates (etching) may occur if too much hydrogen chloride byproduct is present.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Silicon VPE may also use silane, dichlorosilane, and trichlorosilane source gases.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] VPE is sometimes classified by the chemistry of the source gases, such as hydride VPE (HVPE) and metalorganic VPE (MOVPE or MOCVD).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The reaction chamber where this process takes place may be heated by lamps located outside the chamber.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] A common technique used in compound semiconductor growth is molecular beam epitaxy (MBE).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In this method, a source material is heated to produce an evaporated beam of particles, which travel through a very high vacuum (10−8 Pa; practically free space) to the substrate and start epitaxial growth.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Chemical beam epitaxy, on the other hand, is an ultra-high vacuum process that uses gas phase precursors to generate the molecular beam.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Another widely used technique in microelectronics and nanotechnology is atomic layer epitaxy, in which precursor gases are alternatively pulsed into a chamber, leading to atomic monolayer growth by surface saturation and chemisorption.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Liquid-phase epitaxy (LPE) is a method to grow semiconductor crystal layers from the melt on solid substrates.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] This happens at temperatures well below the melting point of the deposited semiconductor.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The semiconductor is dissolved in the melt of another material.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] At conditions that are close to the equilibrium between dissolution and deposition, the deposition of the semiconductor crystal on the substrate is relatively fast and uniform.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The most used substrate is indium phosphide (InP).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Other substrates like glass or ceramic can be applied for special applications.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] To facilitate nucleation, and to avoid tension in the grown layer the thermal expansion coefficient of substrate and grown layer should be similar.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Centrifugal liquid-phase epitaxy is used commercially to make thin layers of silicon, germanium, and gallium arsenide.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Centrifugally formed film growth is a process used to form thin layers of materials by using a centrifuge.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The process has been used to create silicon for thin-film solar cells and far-infrared photodetectors.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Temperature and centrifuge spin rate are used to control layer growth.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Centrifugal LPE has the capability to create dopant concentration gradients while the solution is held at constant temperature.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Solid-phase epitaxy (SPE) is a transition between the amorphous and crystalline phases of a material.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] It is usually produced by depositing a film of amorphous material on a crystalline substrate, then heating it to crystallize the film.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The single-crystal substrate serves as a template for crystal growth.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The annealing step used to recrystallize or heal silicon layers amorphized during ion implantation is also considered to be a type of solid phase epitaxy.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The impurity segregation and redistribution at the growing crystal-amorphous layer interface during this process is used to incorporate low-solubility dopants in metals and silicon.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] An epitaxial layer can be doped during deposition by adding impurities to the source gas, such as arsine, phosphine, or diborane.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Dopants in the source gas, liberated by evaporation or wet etching of the surface, may also diffuse into the epitaxial layer and cause *autodoping*.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The concentration of impurity in the gas phase determines its concentration in the deposited film.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Doping can also be achieved by a site-competition technique, where the growth precursor ratios are tuned to enhance the incorporation of vacancies, specific dopant species or vacant-dopant clusters into the lattice.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Additionally, the high temperatures at which epitaxy is performed may allow dopants to diffuse into the growing layer from other layers in the wafer (*out-diffusion*).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In mineralogy, epitaxy is the overgrowth of one mineral on another in an orderly way, such that certain crystal directions of the two minerals are aligned.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] This occurs when some planes in the lattices of the overgrowth and the substrate have similar spacings between atoms.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] If the crystals of both minerals are well formed so that the directions of the crystallographic axes are clear then the epitaxic relationship can be deduced just by a visual inspection.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Sometimes many separate crystals form the overgrowth on a single substrate, and then if there is epitaxy all the overgrowth crystals will have a similar orientation.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The reverse, however, is not necessarily true.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] If the overgrowth crystals have a similar orientation there is probably an epitaxic relationship, but it is not certain.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] For naturally produced minerals, however, the International Mineralogical Association (IMA) definition requires that the two minerals be of different species.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Another man-made application of epitaxy is the making of artificial snow using silver iodide, which is possible because hexagonal silver iodide and ice have similar cell dimensions.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Minerals that have the same structure (isomorphic minerals) may have epitaxic relations.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] An example is albite NaAlSi 3O 8 on microcline KAlSi 3O 8.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Minerals that have the same composition but different structures (polymorphic minerals) may also have epitaxic relations.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Examples are pyrite and marcasite, both FeS2, and sphalerite and wurtzite, both ZnS.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Some pairs of minerals that are not related structurally or compositionally may also exhibit epitaxy.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] A typical example is rutile TiO2 on hematite Fe2O3.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Rutile is tetragonal and hematite is trigonal.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Still, there are directions of similar spacing between the atoms in the (100) plane of rutile (perpendicular to the a axis) and the (001) plane of hematite (perpendicular to the c axis).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In epitaxy, these directions tend to line up with each other, resulting in the axis of the rutile overgrowth being parallel to the c-axis of hematite, and the c-axis of rutile being parallel to one of the axes of hematite.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Another example is hematite Fe3+ 2O 3 on magnetite Fe2+ Fe3+ 2O 4.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The magnetite structure is based on close-packed oxygen anions stacked in an ABC-ABC sequence.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In this packing the close-packed layers are parallel to (111) (a plane that symmetrically "cuts off" a corner of a cube).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The hematite structure is based on close-packed oxygen anions stacked in an AB-AB sequence, which results in a crystal with hexagonal symmetry.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] If the cations were small enough to fit into a truly close-packed structure of oxygen anions then the spacing between the nearest neighbour oxygen sites would be the same for both species.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The radius of the oxygen ion, however, is only 1.36 Å and the Fe cations are big enough to cause some variations.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] The Fe radii vary from 0.49 Å to 0.92 Å, depending on the charge (2+ or 3+) and the coordination number (4 or 8).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Nevertheless, the O spacings are similar for the two minerals hence hematite can readily grow on the (111) faces of magnetite, with hematite (001) parallel to magnetite (111).
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Epitaxy is used in nanotechnology and in semiconductor fabrication.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] Indeed, epitaxy is the only affordable method of high quality crystal growth for many semiconductor materials.
[src:thin-films/epitaxy] In surface science, epitaxy is used to create and study monolayer and multilayer films of adsorbed organic molecules on single crystalline surfaces via scanning tunnelling microscopy.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The source material is, unavoidably, also deposited on most other surfaces in the vacuum chamber, including the fixtures holding the parts.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] PVD can be used as an application to make anisotropic glasses of low molecular weight for organic semiconductors.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The parameter needed to allow the formation of this type of glass is molecular mobility and anisotropic structure at the free surface of the glass.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The configuration of the polymer is important where it needs to be positioned in a lower energy state before the added molecules bury the material through a deposition.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] This process of adding molecules to the structure starts to equilibrate and gain mass and bulk out to have more kinetic stability.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The packing of molecules here through PVD is face-on, meaning not at the long tail end, allows further overlap of pi orbitals as well which also increases the stability of added molecules and the bonds.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The orientation of these added materials is dependent mainly on temperature for when molecules will be deposited or extracted from the molecule.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The equilibration of the molecules is what provides the glass with its anisotropic characteristics.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The anisotropy of these glasses is valuable as it allows a higher charge carrier mobility.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] This process of packing in glass in an anisotropic way is valuable due to its versatility and the fact that glass provides added benefits beyond crystals, such as homogeneity and flexibility of composition.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] By varying the composition and duration of the process, a range of colors can be produced by PVD on stainless steel.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The resulting colored stainless steel product can appear as brass, bronze, and other metals or alloys.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] This PVD-colored stainless steel can be used as exterior cladding for buildings and structures, such as the *Vessel* sculpture in New York City and The Bund in Shanghai.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] It is also used for interior hardware, paneling, and fixtures, and is even used on some consumer electronics, like the Space Gray and Gold finishes of the iPhone and Apple Watch.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] PVD is used to enhance the wear resistance of steel cutting tools' surfaces and decrease the risk of adhesion and sticking between tools and a workpiece.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] This includes tools used in metalworking or plastic injection molding.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] The coating is typically a thin ceramic layer less than 4 μm that has very high hardness and low friction.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] It is necessary to have high hardness of workpieces to ensure dimensional stability of coating to avoid brittling.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] It is possible to combine PVD with a plasma nitriding treatment of steel to increase the load bearing capacity of the coating.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] Chromium nitride (CrN), titanium nitride (TiN), and titanium carbonitride (TiCN) may be used for PVD coating for plastic molding dies.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] PVD coatings are generally used to improve hardness, increase wear resistance, and prevent oxidation.
[src:thin-films/physical-vapor-deposition] They can also be used for aesthetic purposes.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Resputtering is re-emission of the deposited material during the deposition process by ion or atom bombardment.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtered atoms ejected from the target have a wide energy distribution, typically up to tens of eV (100,000 K).
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The sputtered ions (typically only a small fraction of the ejected particles are ionized—on the order of 1 percent) can ballistically fly from the target in straight lines and impact energetically on the substrates or vacuum chamber (causing resputtering).
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Alternatively, at higher gas pressures, the ions collide with the gas atoms that act as a moderator and move diffusively, reaching the substrates or vacuum chamber wall and condensing after undergoing a random walk.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The entire range from high-energy ballistic impact to low-energy thermalized motion is accessible by changing the background gas pressure.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The sputtering gas is often an inert gas such as argon.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] For efficient momentum transfer, the atomic weight of the sputtering gas should be close to the atomic weight of the target, so for sputtering light elements neon is preferable, while for heavy elements krypton or xenon are used.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Reactive gases can also be used to sputter compounds.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The compound can be formed on the target surface, in-flight or on the substrate depending on the process parameters.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The availability of many parameters that control sputter deposition make it a complex process, but also allow experts a large degree of control over the growth and microstructure of the film.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] One of the earliest widespread commercial applications of sputter deposition, which is still one of its most important applications, is in the production of computer hard disks.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtering is used extensively in the semiconductor industry to deposit thin films of various materials in integrated circuit processing.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Thin antireflection coatings on glass for optical applications are also deposited by sputtering.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Because of the low substrate temperatures used, sputtering is an ideal method to deposit contact metals for thin-film transistors.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Another familiar application of sputtering is low-emissivity coatings on glass, used in double-pane window assemblies.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The coating is a multilayer containing silver and metal oxides such as zinc oxide, tin oxide, or titanium dioxide.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] A large industry has developed around tool bit coating using sputtered nitrides, such as titanium nitride, creating the familiar gold colored hard coat.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtering is also used as the process to deposit the metal (e.g., aluminium) layer during the fabrication of CDs and DVDs.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Hard disk surfaces use sputtered CrOx and other sputtered materials.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtering is one of the main processes of manufacturing optical waveguides and is another way for making efficient photovoltaic and thin film solar cells.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In 2022, researchers at IMEC built up lab superconducting qubits with coherence times exceeding 100 μs and an average single-qubit gate fidelity of 99.94%, using CMOS-compatible fabrication techniques such as sputtering deposition and subtractive etch.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputter coating in scanning electron microscopy is a sputter deposition process to cover a specimen with a thin layer of conducting material, typically a metal, such as a gold/palladium (Au/Pd) alloy.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] A conductive coating is needed to prevent charging of a specimen with an electron beam in conventional SEM mode (high vacuum, high voltage).
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] While metal coatings are also useful for increasing signal to noise ratio (heavy metals are good secondary electron emitters), they are of inferior quality when X-ray spectroscopy is employed.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] For this reason when using X-ray spectroscopy a carbon coating is preferred.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] An important advantage of sputter deposition is that even materials with very high melting points are easily sputtered while evaporation of these materials in a resistance evaporator or Knudsen cell is problematic or impossible.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputter deposited films have a composition close to that of the source material.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The difference is due to different elements spreading differently because of their different mass (light elements are deflected more easily by the gas) but this difference is constant.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtered films typically have a better adhesion on the substrate than evaporated films.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] A target contains a large amount of material and is maintenance free making the technique suited for ultrahigh vacuum applications.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtering sources contain no hot parts (to avoid heating they are typically water cooled) and are compatible with reactive gases such as oxygen.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtering can be performed top-down while evaporation must be performed bottom-up.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Advanced processes such as epitaxial growth are possible.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Some disadvantages of the sputtering process are that the process is more difficult to combine with a lift-off for structuring the film.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] This is because the diffuse transport, characteristic of sputtering, makes a full shadow impossible.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Thus, one cannot fully restrict where the atoms go, which can lead to contamination problems.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Also, active control for layer-by-layer growth is difficult compared to pulsed laser deposition and inert sputtering gases are built into the growing film as impurities.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Pulsed laser deposition is a variant of the sputtering deposition technique in which a laser beam is used for sputtering.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Role of the sputtered and resputtered ions and the background gas is fully investigated during the pulsed laser deposition process.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtering sources often employ magnetrons that utilize strong electric and magnetic fields to confine charged plasma particles close to the surface of the sputter target.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In a magnetic field, electrons follow helical paths around magnetic field lines, undergoing more ionizing collisions with gaseous neutrals near the target surface than would otherwise occur.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] (As the target material is depleted, a "racetrack" erosion profile may appear on the surface of the target.) The sputter gas is typically an inert gas such as argon.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The extra argon ions created as a result of these collisions lead to a higher deposition rate.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The plasma can also be sustained at a lower pressure this way.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The sputtered atoms are neutrally charged and so are unaffected by the magnetic trap.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Charge build-up on insulating targets can be avoided with the use of **RF sputtering** where the sign of the anode-cathode bias is varied at a high rate (commonly 13.56 MHz).
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] RF sputtering works well to produce highly insulating oxide films but with the added expense of RF power supplies and impedance matching networks.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Stray magnetic fields leaking from ferromagnetic targets also disturb the sputtering process.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Specially designed sputter guns with unusually strong permanent magnets must often be used in compensation.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Ion-beam sputtering (IBS) is a method in which the target is external to the ion source.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] A source can work without any magnetic field like in a hot filament ionization gauge.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In a Kaufman source ions are generated by collisions with electrons that are confined by a magnetic field as in a magnetron.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] They are then accelerated by the electric field emanating from a grid toward a target.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] As the ions leave the source they are neutralized by electrons from a second external filament.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] IBS has an advantage in that the energy and flux of ions can be controlled independently.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Since the flux that strikes the target is composed of neutral atoms, either insulating or conducting targets can be sputtered.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] IBS has found application in the manufacture of thin-film heads for disk drives.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] A pressure gradient between the ion source and the sample chamber is generated by placing the gas inlet at the source and shooting through a tube into the sample chamber.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] This saves gas and reduces contamination in UHV applications.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The principal drawback of IBS is the large amount of maintenance required to keep the ion source operating.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In reactive sputtering, the sputtered particles from a target material undergo a chemical reaction aiming to deposit a film with different composition on a certain substrate.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The chemical reaction that the particles undergo is with a reactive gas introduced into the sputtering chamber such as oxygen or nitrogen, enabling the production of oxide and nitride films, respectively.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The introduction of an additional element to the process, i.e. the reactive gas, has a significant influence in the desired depositions, making it more difficult to find ideal working points.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Like so, the wide majority of reactive-based sputtering processes are characterized by an hysteresis-like behavior, thus needing proper control of the involved parameters, e.g. the partial pressure of working (or inert) and reactive gases, to undermine it.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Berg et al. proposed a significant model, i.e.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Berg Model, to estimate the impact upon addition of the reactive gas in sputtering processes.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Generally, the influence of the reactive gas' relative pressure and flow were estimated in accordance to the target's erosion and film's deposition rate on the desired substrate.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The composition of the film can be controlled by varying the relative pressures of the inert and reactive gases.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Film stoichiometry is an important parameter for optimizing functional properties like the stress in SiNx and the index of refraction of SiOx.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In ion-assisted deposition (IAD), the substrate is exposed to a secondary ion beam operating at a lower power than the sputter gun.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Usually a Kaufman source, like that used in IBS, supplies the secondary beam.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] IAD can be used to deposit carbon in diamond-like form on a substrate.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Any carbon atoms landing on the substrate which fail to bond properly in the diamond crystal lattice will be knocked off by the secondary beam.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] NASA used this technique to experiment with depositing diamond films on turbine blades in the 1980s.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] IAD is used in other important industrial applications such as creating tetrahedral amorphous carbon surface coatings on hard disk platters and hard transition metal nitride coatings on medical implants.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Sputtering may also be performed by remote generation of a high density plasma.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The plasma is generated in a side chamber opening into the main process chamber, containing the target and the substrate to be coated.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] As the plasma is generated remotely, and not from the target itself (as in conventional magnetron sputtering), the ion current to the target is independent of the voltage applied to the target.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] HiPIMS is a method for physical vapor deposition of thin films which is based on magnetron sputter deposition.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] HiPIMS utilizes extremely high power densities of the order of kW/cm2 in short pulses (impulses) of tens of microseconds at low duty cycle of < 10%.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Gas flow sputtering makes use of the hollow cathode effect, the same effect by which hollow cathode lamps operate.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In gas flow sputtering a working gas like argon is led through an opening in a metal subjected to a negative electrical potential.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Enhanced plasma densities occur in the hollow cathode, if the pressure in the chamber *p* and a characteristic dimension *L* of the hollow cathode obey the Paschen's law 0.5 Pa·m < *p*·*L* < 5 Pa·m.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] This causes a high flux of ions on the surrounding surfaces and a large sputter effect.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The hollow-cathode based gas flow sputtering may thus be associated with large deposition rates up to values of a few μm/min.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Thornton applied the structure zone model for the description of thin film morphologies to sputter deposition.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In a study on metallic layers prepared by DC sputtering, he extended the structure zone concept initially introduced by Movchan and Demchishin for evaporated films.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Thornton introduced a further structure zone T, which was observed at low argon pressures and characterized by densely packed fibrous grains.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The most important point of this extension was to emphasize the pressure *p* as a decisive process parameter.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] In particular, if hyperthermal techniques like sputtering etc. are used for the sublimation of source atoms, the pressure governs via the mean free path the energy distribution with which they impinge on the surface of the growing film.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Next to the deposition temperature *Td* the chamber pressure or mean free path should thus always be specified when considering a deposition process.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Since sputter deposition belongs to the group of plasma-assisted processes, next to neutral atoms also charged species (like argon ions) hit the surface of the growing film, and this component may exert a large effect.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] Denoting the fluxes of the arriving ions and atoms by *Ji* and *Ja*, it turned out that the magnitude of the *Ji/Ja* ratio plays a decisive role on the microstructure and morphology obtained in the film.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] The effect of ion bombardment may quantitatively be derived from structural parameters like preferred orientation of crystallites or texture and from the state of residual stress.
[src:thin-films/sputter-deposition] It has been shown recently that textures and residual stresses may arise in gas-flow sputtered Ti layers that compare to those obtained in macroscopic Ti work pieces subjected to a severe plastic deformation by shot peening.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A **thin film** is a layer of material ranging from fractions of a nanometer (monolayer) to several micrometers in thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The controlled synthesis of materials as thin films (a process referred to as deposition) is a fundamental step in many applications.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A familiar example is the household mirror, which typically has a thin metal coating on the back of a sheet of glass to form a reflective interface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The process of silvering was once commonly used to produce mirrors, while more recently the metal layer is deposited using techniques such as sputtering.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] It is also being applied to pharmaceuticals, via thin-film drug delivery.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A stack of thin films is called a multilayer.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In addition to their applied interest, thin films play an important role in the development and study of materials with new and unique properties.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Examples include multiferroic materials, and superlattices that allow the study of quantum phenomena.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Nucleation is an important step in growth that helps determine the final structure of a thin film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Many growth methods rely on nucleation control such as atomic-layer epitaxy (atomic layer deposition).
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Nucleation can be modeled by characterizing surface process of adsorption, desorption, and surface diffusion.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Adsorption is the interaction of a vapor atom or molecule with a substrate surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The interaction is characterized by the sticking coefficient, the fraction of incoming species thermally equilibrated with the surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Desorption reverses adsorption where a previously adsorbed molecule overcomes the bounding energy and leaves the substrate surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The two types of adsorptions, physisorption and chemisorption, are distinguished by the strength of atomic interactions.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Physisorption describes the van der Waals bonding between a stretched or bent molecule and the surface characterized by adsorption energy $E_{p}$ .
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Evaporated molecules rapidly lose kinetic energy and reduces its free energy by bonding with surface atoms.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Chemisorption describes the strong electron transfer (ionic or covalent bond) of molecule with substrate atoms characterized by adsorption energy $E_{c}$ .
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The process of physic- and chemisorption can be visualized by the potential energy as a function of distance.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The equilibrium distance for physisorption is further from the surface than chemisorption.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The transition from physisorbed to chemisorbed states are governed by the effective energy barrier $E_{a}$ .
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Crystal surfaces have specific bonding sites with larger $E_{a}$ values that would preferentially be populated by vapor molecules to reduce the overall free energy.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] These stable sites are often found on step edges, vacancies and screw dislocations.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] After the most stable sites become filled, the adatom-adatom (vapor molecule) interaction becomes important.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Nucleation kinetics can be modeled considering only adsorption and desorption.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] First consider case where there are no mutual adatom interactions, no clustering or interaction with step edges.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Adsorption can also be modeled by different isotherms such as Langmuir model and BET model.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The Langmuir model derives an equilibrium constant b based on the adsorption reaction of vapor adatom with vacancy on the substrate surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The BET model expands further and allows adatoms deposition on previously adsorbed adatoms without interaction between adjacent piles of atoms.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The resulting derived surface coverage is in terms of the equilibrium vapor pressure and applied pressure.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] As an important note, surface crystallography and differ from the bulk to minimize the overall free electronic and bond energies due to the broken bonds at the surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This can result in a new equilibrium position known as "selvedge", where the parallel bulk lattice symmetry is preserved.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This phenomenon can cause deviations from theoretical calculations of nucleation.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Surface diffusion describes the lateral motion of adsorbed atoms moving between energy minima on the substrate surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Diffusion most readily occurs between positions with lowest intervening potential barriers.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Surface diffusion can be measured using glancing-angle ion scattering.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In addition to adatom migration, clusters of adatom can coalesce or deplete.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Cluster coalescence through processes, such as Ostwald ripening and sintering, occur in response to reduce the total surface energy of the system.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Ostwald repining describes the process in which islands of adatoms with various sizes grow into larger ones at the expense of smaller ones.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Sintering is the coalescence mechanism when the islands contact and join.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The act of applying a thin film to a surface is *thin-film deposition* – any technique for depositing a thin film of material onto a substrate or onto previously deposited layers.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] "Thin" is a relative term, but most deposition techniques control layer thickness within a few tens of nanometres.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Molecular beam epitaxy, the Langmuir–Blodgett method, atomic layer deposition and molecular layer deposition allow a single layer of atoms or molecules to be deposited at a time.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Similar processes are sometimes used where thickness is not important: for instance, the purification of copper by electroplating, and the deposition of silicon and enriched uranium by a chemical vapor deposition-like process after gas-phase processing.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Deposition techniques fall into two broad categories, depending on whether the process is primarily chemical or physical.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Here, a fluid precursor undergoes a chemical change at a solid surface, leaving a solid layer.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] An everyday example is the formation of soot on a cool object when it is placed inside a flame.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Since the fluid surrounds the solid object, deposition happens on every surface, with little regard to direction; thin films from chemical deposition techniques tend to be *conformal*, rather than *directional*.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Plating relies on liquid precursors, often a solution of water with a salt of the metal to be deposited.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Some plating processes are driven entirely by reagents in the solution (usually for noble metals), but by far the most commercially important process is electroplating.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Chemical solution deposition or chemical bath deposition uses a liquid precursor, usually a solution of organometallic powders dissolved in an organic solvent.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This is a relatively inexpensive, simple thin-film process that produces stoichiometrically accurate crystalline phases.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This technique is also known as the sol-gel method because the 'sol' (or solution) gradually evolves towards the formation of a gel-like diphasic system.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The Langmuir–Blodgett method uses molecules floating on top of an aqueous subphase.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The packing density of molecules is controlled, and the packed monolayer is transferred on a solid substrate by controlled withdrawal of the solid substrate from the subphase.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This allows creating thin films of various molecules such as nanoparticles, polymers and lipids with controlled particle packing density and layer thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Spin coating or spin casting, uses a liquid precursor, or sol-gel precursor deposited onto a smooth, flat substrate which is subsequently spun at a high velocity to centrifugally spread the solution over the substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The speed at which the solution is spun and the viscosity of the sol determine the ultimate thickness of the deposited film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Repeated depositions can be carried out to increase the thickness of films as desired.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thermal treatment is often carried out in order to crystallize the amorphous spin coated film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Such crystalline films can exhibit certain preferred orientations after crystallization on single crystal substrates.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Dip coating is similar to spin coating in that a liquid precursor or sol-gel precursor is deposited on a substrate, but in this case the substrate is completely submerged in the solution and then withdrawn under controlled conditions.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] By controlling the withdrawal speed, the evaporation conditions (principally the humidity, temperature) and the volatility/viscosity of the solvent, the film thickness, homogeneity and nanoscopic morphology are controlled.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] There are two evaporation regimes: the capillary zone at very low withdrawal speeds, and the draining zone at faster evaporation speeds.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Chemical vapor deposition generally uses a gas-phase precursor, often a halide or hydride of the element to be deposited.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In the case of metalorganic vapour-phase epitaxy, an organometallic gas is used.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Commercial techniques often use very low pressures of precursor gas.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Plasma-enhanced chemical vapor deposition uses an ionized vapor, or plasma, as a precursor.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Unlike the soot example above, this method relies on electromagnetic means (electric current, microwave excitation), rather than a chemical-reaction, to produce a plasma.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Atomic layer deposition and its sister technique molecular layer deposition, uses gaseous precursor to deposit conformal thin film's one layer at a time.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The process is split up into two half reactions, run in sequence and repeated for each layer, in order to ensure total layer saturation before beginning the next layer.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Therefore, one reactant is deposited first, and then the second reactant is deposited, during which a chemical reaction occurs on the substrate, forming the desired composition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] As a result of the stepwise, the process is slower than chemical vapor deposition; however, it can be run at low temperatures.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] When performed on polymeric substrates, atomic layer deposition can become sequential infiltration synthesis, where the reactants diffuse into the polymer and interact with functional groups on the polymer chains.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Physical deposition uses mechanical, electromechanical or thermodynamic means to produce a thin film of solid.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] An everyday example is the formation of frost.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The material to be deposited is placed in an energetic, entropic environment, so that particles of material escape its surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Facing this source is a cooler surface which draws energy from these particles as they arrive, allowing them to form a solid layer.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The whole system is kept in a vacuum deposition chamber, to allow the particles to travel as freely as possible.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Since particles tend to follow a straight path, films deposited by physical means are commonly *directional*, rather than *conformal*.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A thermal evaporator that uses an electric resistance heater to melt the material and raise its vapor pressure to a useful range.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This is done in a high vacuum, both to allow the vapor to reach the substrate without reacting with or scattering against other gas-phase atoms in the chamber, and reduce the incorporation of impurities from the residual gas in the vacuum chamber.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Only materials with a much higher vapor pressure than the heating element can be deposited without contamination of the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Molecular beam epitaxy is a particularly sophisticated form of thermal evaporation.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] An electron beam evaporator fires a high-energy beam from an electron gun to boil a small spot of material; since the heating is not uniform, lower vapor pressure materials can be deposited.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The beam is usually bent through an angle of 270° in order to ensure that the gun filament is not directly exposed to the evaporant flux.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Typical deposition rates for electron beam evaporation range from 1 to 10 nanometres per second.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In molecular beam epitaxy, slow streams of an element can be directed at the substrate, so that material deposits one atomic layer at a time.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Compounds such as gallium arsenide are usually deposited by repeatedly applying a layer of one element (i.e., gallium), then a layer of the other (i.e., arsenic), so that the process is chemical, as well as physical; this is known also as atomic layer deposition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] If the precursors in use are organic, then the technique is called molecular layer deposition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The beam of material can be generated by either physical means (that is, by a furnace) or by a chemical reaction (chemical beam epitaxy).
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Sputtering relies on a plasma (usually a noble gas, such as argon) to knock material from a "target" a few atoms at a time.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The target can be kept at a relatively low temperature, since the process is not one of evaporation, making this one of the most flexible deposition techniques.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] It is especially useful for compounds or mixtures, where different components would otherwise tend to evaporate at different rates.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Note, sputtering's step coverage is more or less conformal.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] It is also widely used in optical media.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The manufacturing of all formats of CD, DVD, and BD are done with the help of this technique.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] It is a fast technique and also it provides a good thickness control.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Presently, nitrogen and oxygen gases are also being used in sputtering.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Pulsed laser deposition systems work by an ablation process.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Pulses of focused laser light vaporize the surface of the target material and convert it to plasma; this plasma usually reverts to a gas before it reaches the substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thermal laser epitaxy uses focused light from a continuous-wave laser to thermally evaporate sources of material.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] By adjusting the power density of the laser beam, the evaporation of any solid, non-radioactive element is possible.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The resulting atomic vapor is then deposited upon a substrate, which is also heated via a laser beam.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The vast range of substrate and deposition temperatures allows of the epitaxial growth of various elements considered challenging by other thin-film growth techniques.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Cathodic arc deposition (arc-physical vapor deposition), which is a kind of ion beam deposition where an electrical arc is created that blasts ions from the cathode.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The arc has an extremely high power density resulting in a high level of ionization (30–100%), multiply charged ions, neutral particles, clusters and macro-particles (droplets).
[src:thin-films/thin-film] If a reactive gas is introduced during the evaporation process, dissociation, ionization and excitation can occur during interaction with the ion flux and a compound film will be deposited.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Electrohydrodynamic deposition (electrospray deposition) is a relatively new process of thin-film deposition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The liquid to be deposited, either in the form of nanoparticle solution or simply a solution, is fed to a small capillary nozzle (usually metallic) which is connected to a high voltage.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The substrate on which the film has to be deposited is connected to ground.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Through the influence of electric field, the liquid coming out of the nozzle takes a conical shape (Taylor cone) and at the apex of the cone a thin jet emanates which disintegrates into very fine and small positively charged droplets under the influence of Rayleigh charge limit.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The droplets keep getting smaller and smaller and ultimately get deposited on the substrate as a uniform thin layer.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Frank–van der Merwe growth ("layer-by-layer").
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In this growth mode the adsorbate-surface and adsorbate-adsorbate interactions are balanced.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This type of growth requires lattice matching, and hence considered an "ideal" growth mechanism.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Stranski–Krastanov growth ("joint islands" or "layer-plus-island").
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In this growth mode the adsorbate-surface interactions are stronger than adsorbate-adsorbate interactions.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In this growth mode the adsorbate-adsorbate interactions are stronger than adsorbate-surface interactions, hence "islands" are formed right away.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] There are three distinct stages of stress evolution that arise during Volmer-Weber film deposition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The first stage consists of the nucleation of individual atomic islands.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] During this first stage, the overall observed stress is very low.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The second stage commences as these individual islands coalesce and begin to impinge on each other, resulting in an increase in the overall tensile stress in the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This increase in overall tensile stress can be attributed to the formation of grain boundaries upon island coalescence that results in interatomic forces acting over the newly formed grain boundaries.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The magnitude of this generated tensile stress depends on the density of the formed grain boundaries, as well as their grain-boundary energies.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] During this stage, the thickness of the film is not uniform because of the random nature of the island coalescence but is measured as the average thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The third and final stage of the Volmer-Weber film growth begins when the morphology of the film's surface is unchanging with film thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] During this stage, the overall stress in the film can remain tensile, or become compressive.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] On a stress-thickness vs. thickness plot, an overall compressive stress is represented by a negative slope, and an overall tensile stress is represented by a positive slope.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The overall shape of the stress-thickness vs. thickness curve depends on various processing conditions (such as temperature, growth rate, and material).
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Koch states that there are three different modes of Volmer-Weber growth.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Zone I behavior is characterized by low grain growth in subsequent film layers and is associated with low atomic mobility.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Koch suggests that Zone I behavior can be observed at lower temperatures.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The zone I mode typically has small columnar grains in the final film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The second mode of Volmer-Weber growth is classified as Zone T, where the grain size at the surface of the film deposition increases with film thickness, but the grain size in the deposited layers below the surface does not change.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Zone T-type films are associated with higher atomic mobilities, higher deposition temperatures, and V-shaped final grains.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The final mode of proposed Volmer-Weber growth is Zone II type growth, where the grain boundaries in the bulk of the film at the surface are mobile, resulting in large yet columnar grains.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This growth mode is associated with the highest atomic mobility and deposition temperature.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] There is also a possibility of developing a mixed Zone T/Zone II type structure, where the grains are mostly wide and columnar, but do experience slight growth as their thickness approaches the surface of the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Although Koch focuses mostly on temperature to suggest a potential zone mode, factors such as deposition rate can also influence the final film microstructure.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A subset of thin-film deposition processes and applications is focused on the so-called epitaxial growth of materials, the deposition of crystalline thin films that grow following the crystalline structure of the substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The term epitaxy comes from the Greek roots epi (ἐπί), meaning "above", and taxis (τάξις), meaning "an ordered manner".
[src:thin-films/thin-film] It can be translated as "arranging upon".
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The term **homoepitaxy** refers to the specific case in which a film of the same material is grown on a crystalline substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This technology is used, for instance, to grow a film which is more pure than the substrate, has a lower density of defects, and to fabricate layers having different doping levels.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] **Heteroepitaxy** refers to the case in which the film being deposited is different from the substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Techniques used for epitaxial growth of thin films include molecular beam epitaxy, chemical vapor deposition, and pulsed laser deposition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thin films may be biaxially loaded via stresses originated from their interface with a substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Epitaxial thin films may experience stresses from misfit strains between the coherent lattices of the film and substrate, and from the restructuring of the surface triple junction.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thermal stress is common in thin films grown at elevated temperatures due to differences in thermal expansion coefficients with the substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Differences in interfacial energy and the growth and coalescence of grains contribute to intrinsic stress in thin films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] These intrinsic stresses can be a function of film thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] These stresses may be tensile or compressive and can cause cracking, buckling, or delamination along the surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In epitaxial films, initially deposited atomic layers may have coherent lattice planes with the substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] However, past a critical thickness misfit dislocations will form leading to relaxation of stresses in the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Films may experience a dilatational transformation strain $e_{T}$ relative to its substrate due to a volume change in the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Volume changes that cause dilatational strain may come from changes in temperature, defects, or phase transformations.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A temperature change will induce a volume change if the film and substrate thermal expansion coefficients are different.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The creation or annihilation of defects such as vacancies, dislocations, and grain boundaries will cause a volume change through densification.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Phase transformations and concentration changes will cause volume changes via lattice distortions.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A mismatch of thermal expansion coefficients between the film and substrate will cause thermal strain during a temperature change.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] where $\varepsilon$ is the elastic strain, $\alpha _{f}$ is the thermal expansion coefficient of the film, $\alpha _{s}$ is the thermal expansion coefficient of the substrate, T is the temperature, and $T_{0}$ is the initial temperature of the film and substrate when it is in a stress-free state.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] For example, if a film is deposited onto a substrate with a lower thermal expansion coefficient at high temperatures, then cooled to room temperature, a positive elastic strain will be created.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In this case, the film will develop tensile stresses.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Unlike thermal and epitaxial strain, which are driven by external factors such as temperature and substrate lattice parameters, growth strain originates from within the film itself.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A change in density due to the creation or destruction of defects, phase changes, or compositional changes after the film is grown on the substrate will generate a growth strain.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Such as in the Stranski–Krastanov mode, where the layer of film is strained to fit the substrate due to an increase in supersaturation and interfacial energy which shifts from island to island.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A film experiencing growth strains will be under biaxial tensile strain conditions, generating tensile stresses in biaxial directions in order to match the substrate dimensions.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Epitaxial strain refers to the elastic deformation of a thin film as a result of lattice mismatch with the single-crystal substrate it is deposited upon.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The crystal structure and properties of thin films are significantly influenced by epitaxial strain.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Epitaxial strain in thin films has been used to tailor various functional properties such as the dielectric constants of ferroelectric materials, the Curie temperature of superconducting materials.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] where $a_{s}$ and $a_{f}$ are the lattice parameters of the substrate and film, respectively.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] It is assumed that the substrate is rigid due to its relative thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Therefore, all of the elastic strain occurs in the film to match the substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Beyond lattice mismatch, epitaxial strain is also influenced by the surface morphology of substrates.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Substrates for epitaxial thin-film growth are often prepared via annealing to have atomically flat steps.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] However, the size of these substrate steps relative to the unit cell size of the film is often mismatched and has been shown to contribute to the strain of the film, and thus, further impact the film's properties.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Epitaxial strain is a function of film thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] For thin films, there is a critical thickness below which the film is epitaxially strained and above which it is energetically favorable for the film to become relaxed by the introduction of defects such as dislocations.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The figure below depicts the effects of film thickness on epitaxial strain.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Since the initial film has a larger lattice than that of the substrate, the in-plane lattice parameter of the film when strained (t < tcrit) is reduced to match that of the substrate, and due to Poisson's ratio, the surface normal lattice parameter is expected to increase.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] When the film becomes relaxed (t > tcrit), dislocations at the film/substrate interface allow the lattice parameters of the film to approach those of the bulk material.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Multiple models for critical thickness have been developed over the last 50 years.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The first model to predict the critical thickness was developed by Matthews and Blakeslee (MB) in 1974, who derived their model through a force-balancing argument between the driving force for dislocation glide and the resistance from lattice mismatch stress.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The MB model was developed for the specific case of a thin film on a thick substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] However, subsequent experimental studies – particularly on SiGe thin films – found disagreement between the MB predictions and experimental data.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The deviations between results and the model could likely be attributed to the fact that the MB theory neglects dislocation-dislocation interactions and dislocation nucleation mechanisms.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] To address these limitations of the MB model, other scientists proceeded to develop more advanced models that would more accurately predict experimental results.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In the late 1980s, Dodson and Tsao considered an excess stress argument rather than a force-balancing argument to develop the DT model, which agreed well with experimental results for SiGe thin films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In 1996, Freund and Nix considered an energy-based argument to generalize the MB model for the case of a compliant substrate and epitaxial film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The stresses in films deposited on flat substrates such as wafers can be calculated by measuring the curvature of the wafer due to the strain by the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Using optical setups, such as those with lasers, allow for whole wafer characterization pre and post deposition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Lasers are reflected off the wafer in a grid pattern and distortions in the grid are used to calculate the curvature as well as measure the optical constants.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Strain in thin films can also be measured by x-ray diffraction, Raman spectroscopy, or by milling a section of the film using a focused ion beam and monitoring the relaxation via scanning electron microscopy.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A common method for determining the stress evolution of a film is to measure the wafer curvature during its deposition.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The assumptions made regarding the Stoney formula assume that the film and substrate are smaller than the lateral size of the wafer and that the stress is uniform across the surface.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] where z is the direction normal to the substrate and $\sigma (z)$ represents the in-place stress at a particular height of the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The stress thickness (or force per unit width) is represented by $\langle \sigma \rangle h_{f}$ is an important quantity as it is directionally proportional to the curvature by ${\frac {6}{M_{s}h_{s}^{2}}}$ .
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Because of this proportionality, measuring the curvature of a film at a given film thickness can directly determine the stress in the film at that thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The curvature of a wafer is determined by the average stress of in the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] can show how the intrinsic stress is changing at any given point.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Nanoindentation is a popular method of measuring the mechanical properties of films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Measurements can be used to compare coated and uncoated films to reveal the effects of surface treatment on both elastic and plastic responses of the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Load-displacement curves may reveal information about cracking, delamination, and plasticity in both the film and substrate.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The Oliver and Pharr method can be used to evaluate nanoindentation results for hardness and elastic modulus evaluation by the use of axisymmetric indenter geometries like a spherical indenter.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This method assumes that during unloading, only elastic deformations are recovered (where reverse plastic deformation is negligible).
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The parameter P designates the load, h is the displacement relative to the undeformed coating surface and $h_{f}$ is the final penetration depth after unloading.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Where $E_{eff}$ is the effective elastic modulus and takes into account elastic displacements in the specimen and indenter.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This relation can also be applied to elastic-plastic contact, which is not affected by pile-up and sink-in during indentation.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Due to the low thickness of the films, accidental probing of the substrate is a concern.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] To avoid indenting beyond the film and into the substrate, penetration depths are often kept to less than 10% of the film thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] For a conical or pyramidal indenters, the indentation depth scales as $a/t$ where a is the radius of the contact circle and t is the film thickness.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The ratio of penetration depth h and film thickness can be used as a scale parameter for soft films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] X-ray diffraction is a powerful non-destructive technique for strain measurement in crystalline thin films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Accurate measurements of diffraction peak angular positions can be used to determine the lattice parameters of a thin film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Deviation from the unstrained lattice parameters yields the strain present in the film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] where $\nu$ is the film's Poisson's ratio.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Micro-Raman spectroscopy is often employed to noninvasively map strain states in monocrystalline thin films with high spatial resolution.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Raman peak frequencies are sensitive to temperature, polarization, charge and defect density, as well as strain.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Compressive strain typically blue shifts (increases) characteristic Raman peak frequencies while tensile strain results in redshift (decrease).
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thickness-dependent strain can be directly calculated from shift magnitudes as long as the appropriate phonon frequency shift-strain coefficient (phonon deformation potential) is known and there are minimal variations in charge and defect density across the region of interest.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] High resolution TEM (HRTEM) or scanning TEM (STEM) can be used to directly measure interplanar distances in crystalline materials.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Diffraction methods such as nanobeam electron diffraction (NBED) measure reciprocal interplanar distances.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] These techniques can be leveraged in a TEM to measure crystal lattice strain in two dimensions.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Comparison of these distances in strained and unstrained regions in a crystal yields the strain value.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Geometric phase analysis (GPA), analyzes local variations in the Fourier components of lattice fringes to generate quantitative two dimensional strain maps from high resolution TEM lattice images with near-atomic resolution.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Additionally, misfit dislocations and other strain-related defects can be directly imaged using diffraction contrast in TEM images.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Higher-order Laue zone (HOLZ) features can be accurately measured using convergent beam electron diffraction.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This technique constrains sample thickness and orientation, but it offers exceptional sensitivity, capable of measuring less than 0.1 picometer lattice parameter variation.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This enables the determination of strain and texture orientation variation in individual grains of polycrystalline films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Stress and relaxation of stresses in films can influence the materials properties of the film, such as mass transport in microelectronics applications.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Therefore, precautions are taken to either mitigate or produce such stresses; for example a buffer layer may be deposited between the substrate and film.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Strain engineering is also used to produce various phase and domain structures in thin films such as in the domain structure of the ferroelectric Lead Zirconate Titanate (PZT).
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In the physical sciences, a **multilayer** or **stratified medium** is a stack of different thin films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Typically, a multilayer medium is made for a specific purpose.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Since layers are thin with respect to some relevant length scale, interface effects are much more important than in bulk materials, giving rise to novel physical properties.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The term "multilayer" is *not* an extension of "monolayer" and "bilayer", which describe a *single* layer that is one or two molecules thick.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A multilayer medium rather consists of several thin films.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The usage of thin films for decorative coatings probably represents their oldest application.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] 100 nm thin gold leaves that were already used in ancient India more than 5000 years ago.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] It may also be understood as any form of painting, although this kind of work is generally considered as an arts craft rather than an engineering or scientific discipline.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Today, thin-film materials of variable thickness and high refractive index like titanium dioxide are often applied for decorative coatings on glass for instance, causing a rainbow-color appearance like oil on water.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] In addition, intransparent gold-colored surfaces may either be prepared by sputtering of gold or titanium nitride.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] These layers serve in both reflective and refractive systems.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Large-area (reflective) mirrors became available during the 19th century and were produced by sputtering of metallic silver or aluminum on glass.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Refractive lenses for optical instruments like cameras and microscopes typically exhibit aberrations, i.e. non-ideal refractive behavior.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] While large sets of lenses had to be lined up along the optical path previously, nowadays, the coating of optical lenses with transparent multilayers of titanium dioxide, silicon nitride or silicon oxide etc. may correct these aberrations.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A well-known example for the progress in optical systems by thin-film technology is represented by the only a few mm wide lens in smart phone cameras.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Other examples are given by anti-reflection coatings on eyeglasses or solar panels.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thin films are often deposited to protect an underlying work piece from external influences.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The protection may operate by minimizing the contact with the exterior medium in order to reduce the diffusion from the medium to the work piece or vice versa.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] For instance, plastic lemonade bottles are frequently coated by anti-diffusion layers to avoid the out-diffusion of CO2, into which carbonic acid decomposes that was introduced into the beverage under high pressure.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Another example is represented by thin TiN films in microelectronic chips separating electrically conducting aluminum lines from the embedding insulator SiO2 in order to suppress the formation of Al2O3.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Often, thin films serve as protection against abrasion between mechanically moving parts.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Examples for the latter application are diamond-like carbon layers used in car engines or thin films made of nanocomposites.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thin layers from elemental metals like copper, aluminum, gold or silver etc. and alloys have found numerous applications in electrical devices.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Due to their high electrical conductivity they are able to transport electrical currents or supply voltages.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thin metal layers serve in conventional electrical system, for instance, as Cu layers on printed circuit boards, as the outer ground conductor in coaxial cables and various other forms like sensors etc.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] A major field of application became their use in integrated passive devices and integrated circuits, where the electrical network among active and passive devices like transistors and capacitors etc. is built up from thin Al or Cu layers.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] These layers dispose of thicknesses in the range of a few 100 nm up to a few μm, and they are often embedded into a few nm thin titanium nitride layers in order to block a chemical reaction with the surrounding dielectric like SiO2.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The figure shows a micrograph of a laterally structured TiN/Al/TiN metal stack in a microelectronic chip.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Heterostructures of gallium nitride and similar semiconductors can lead to electrons being bound to a sub-nanometric layer, effectively behaving as a two-dimensional electron gas.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Quantum effects in such thin films can significantly enhance electron mobility as compared to that of a bulk crystal, which is employed in high-electron-mobility transistors.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Noble metal thin films are used in plasmonic structures such as surface plasmon resonance (SPR) sensors.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Surface plasmon polaritons are surface waves in the optical regime that propagate in between metal-dielectric interfaces; in Kretschmann-Raether configuration for the SPR sensors, a prism is coated with a metallic film through evaporation.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Due to the poor adhesive characteristics of metallic films, germanium, titanium or chromium films are used as intermediate layers to promote stronger adhesion.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Metallic thin films are also used in plasmonic waveguide designs.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thin-film technologies are also being developed as a means of substantially reducing the cost of solar cells.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] The rationale for this is thin-film solar cells are cheaper to manufacture owing to their reduced material costs, energy costs, handling costs and capital costs.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] This is especially represented in the use of printed electronics (roll-to-roll) processes.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thin-film printing technology is being used to apply solid-state lithium polymers to a variety of substrates to create unique batteries for specialized applications.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Thin-film batteries can be deposited directly onto chips or chip packages in any shape or size.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] Flexible batteries can be made by printing onto plastic, thin metal foil, or paper.
[src:thin-films/thin-film] For miniaturising and more precise control of resonance frequency of piezoelectric crystals thin-film bulk acoustic resonators TFBARs/FBARs are developed for oscillators, telecommunication filters and duplexers, and sensor applications.
